  "prompt": "Graph Theory: What does it mean if vertices are adjacent?",
  "response": "In graph theory, vertices (or nodes) are considered to be adjacent if there is an edge connecting them directly. This means that you can move from one vertex to the other via this connecting edge without passing through any other vertices. In an undirected graph, adjacency is a symmetric relation, meaning if vertex A is adjacent to vertex B, then vertex B is also adjacent to vertex A. In a directed graph, adjacency can be asymmetric; vertex A may have an edge pointing to vertex B (making B adjacent to A), but not vice versa unless there is a corresponding edge from B to A. Adjacency is a fundamental concept in graph theory as it signifies a direct connection or relationship between two elements within the graph.",
